{"title_page": "Mayuranathaswami Temple, Mayiladuthurai", "text_new": "{{Infobox Hindu temple\n| name               = Mayuranathaswamy temple\n| image              = Mayuranathar temple16.jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption            = ''Gopura'' of the Mayuranathaswamy Temple\n| map_type        = Tamil Nadu\n| map_caption        = \n| coordinates        = {{coord|11|0|N|79|15|E|type:landmark_region:LK|display=inline,title}}\n| native_name        =  \n| country            = [[India]]\n| state           = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| district           = [[Mayiladuthurai District|Mayiladuthurai ]]\n| location           = [[Mayiladuthurai]]\n| elevation_m        = \n| deity  = Mayuranathaswamy ([[Shiva]])\n| primary_deity_Goddess = \n| utsava_deity_Goddess= \n| facade_direction = \n| temple_tank        = \n| tower              = \n| festivals= \n| architecture       = [[Dravidian architecture|Dravidian]]\n| temple_quantity  = \n| monument_quantity= \n| inscriptions       = \n| year_completed         = \n| creator            = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Mayuranathaswamy Temple, Mayiladuthurai''' or Mayuranathar Temple is a Hindu temple in the town of [[Mayiladuthurai]] (formerly known as '''Mayavaram''' or '''Mayuram''') in the [[Mayiladuthurai District]] of [[Tamil Nadu]] in [[India]]. The temple is dedicated to Lord Mayuranathaswamy,\na form of [[Shiva]], and has given its name to the town itself.<ref name=\"imperialp238\">{{cite book|title=The Imperial Gazetteer of India 1908, Vol 17|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.181655|pages=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.181655/page/n228 238]|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1908}}</ref> The main icon is a  ''[[lingam]]'' and the presiding deity is called Mayuranathar because the Hindu goddess [[Parvathi]] worshipped Shiva here in the form of a ''[[peahen|mayura]]''.\n\nOn the day of the new moon in the Tamil month of ''Aippasi'' (November\u2013December), religious Hindus have a ceremonial bath in the temple tank as it is believed to purify them from sins. An annual dance festival called the Mayura Natyanjali festival is celebrated within the precincts of the temple each year.\n\n== Location ==\n\nThe Mayuranathaswami temple is located in the southern part of [[Mayiladuthurai]] about a mile from the [[Kaveri River]].<ref name=\"surap64\">{{cite book|title=Tourist Guide to Tamil Nadu|publisher=Sura Books|ISBN=978-81-7478-177-2|page=64}}</ref> The temple is  on the [[Chidambaram]]\u2013[[Thanjavur]] highway.<ref name=\"sacredtanksp227\">{{cite book|title=Sacred tanks of South India|publisher=C.P.R. Environmental Education Centre|author=Nanditha Krishna|year=2002|page=227}}</ref>\n\n== Significance ==\n[[Tiruvaiyaru|Thiruvayyaru]], [[Mayiladuthurai]], [[Thiruvidaimarudur|Thiruvidaimaruthur]], [[Thiruvenkadu]], Chayavanam and [[Srivanchiyam]] are considered equivalents of [[Varanasi|Kasi]]. Like in Kasi, where the city is centered around [[Kashi Vishwanath Temple]], the temples in these towns along the banks of river [[Cauvery]], namely [[Aiyarappar temple]] in Thiruvaiyaru, [[Mahalingeswarar Temple, Thiruvidaimarudur|Mahalingeswarar temple]] in [[Thiruvidaimarudur]], Mayuranathaswamy temple in [[Mayiladuthurai]], [[Sayavanam Chayavaneswarar Temple|Chayavaneswarar temple]] in Sayavanam, [[Swetharanyeswarar Temple|Swetharanyeswarar temple]] in [[Thiruvenkadu]], [[Vanchinadha Swamy Temple|Srivanchinadhaswamy Koil]] in [[Srivanchiyam]] are the centerpieces of the towns.<ref>{{cite book|title=Temples of Forgotten Glory: A Wide Angle Exposition|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=ItClDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT172&dq=aiyarappar+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixkLq1o4PpAhXaSH0KHdvOBIkQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=aiyarappar%20temple&f=false|page=172|first=Sekar|last=Venkatraman|isbn=9781645876250|publisher=Notion Press|year=2019}}</ref>\n\nIt is one of the shrines of the 275 [[Paadal Petra Sthalams]] - [[Shiva Temples of Tamil Nadu#Sthalams|Shiva Sthalams]] glorified in the early medieval ''[[Tevaram]]'' poems by Tamil Saivite [[Nayanars|Nayanar]] [[Tirugnanasambandar]].\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Mayuranathar temple18.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Hindu goddess [[Parvathi]] in the form of a [[peahen]] worshipping a ''[[shivalinga]]'']]\nThe presiding deity is a ''swayambhu lingam'' or a self-manifested ''[[lingam]]'', the symbol of the Hindu god [[Shiva]]. Shiva's consort is known by the names Abhayapradhambikai, Abhayambikai, Anjalanayaki and Anjalai.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} There are three smaller shrines to the Hindu god [[Ganesha]] and another to Shiva as [[Nataraja]] or \"Lord of Dance\".<ref name=Meena>{{cite book|title=Temples in South India|last=V.|first=Meena|publisher=Harikumar Arts|location=Kanniyakumari|year=1974|edition=1st|pages=36\u201337}}</ref> One of the sculptures in the temple represent Shiva embracing Goddess Parvathi.<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp271\">[[#Ayyar|Ayyar]], p 271</ref> According to [[Hindu mythology|mythology]], the goddess [[Parvathi]], the consort of [[Shiva]], once offended him.<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp271\" /> Shiva was so annoyed he cursed Parvathi to be born as a lowly [[peahen]].<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp271\" /> Later, when Parvathi repented, Shiva reduced this sentence.<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp271\" /> Parvathi had to pray first at [[Mylapore]] and then at [[Mayiladuthurai]], at the end of which she was ridden of her curse and became known as \"Abhayambal\".<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp271\" /> It is believed that [[Brahma]], [[Lakshmi]], sage [[Agastya]], [[Manmatha]], birds and animals worshipped Mayuranathar.<ref name=Meena/>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Mayuranathar8.jpg|200px|left|Image of the temple|thumb]]\nThe temple was built by the [[Medieval Cholas]].{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} The oldest inscriptions on the temple walls date to the time of [[Kulothunga Chola I]].<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp280\">[[#Ayyar|Ayyar]], p 280</ref> Massive renovations were carried out during  1907-1927 by Devakottai AL.VR.P.Veerappa Chettiar & Pethaperumal Chettiar<ref>https://alvrp.wordpress.com/al-vr-p-history/</ref> In May 1927, a temple entry of [[Dalits]] was organised on a big scale by the proponents of the [[Self Respect Movement]] thereby resulting in a huge clash.<ref name=\"rajathuaip224\">{{cite book|title=\tTowards a non-Brahmin millennium: from Iyothee Thass to Periyar|author=S. V. Rajathurai|publisher=Samya|year=1998|page=224|ISBN=978-81-85604-37-4}}</ref>\n\n== Architecture ==\n\nThe temple complex is {{convert|719|ft|m}} long and {{convert|520|ft|m}} wide.<ref>http://temple.dinamalar.com/en/new_en.php?id=214</ref> The ''gopura'' at the eastern entrance to the temple is nine storeys high<ref name=\"surap64\" /> and measures {{convert|194|ft|m}}.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} The idol of [[Durga]] near the northern entrance of the temple is expertly sculpted and differs from those in other temples.<ref name=\"surap64\" /> On the temple walls, there is the sculpture of a devotee trying to sever his head as an offering to the God.<ref name=\"surap64\" />\n\nThere is an expansive temple tank in the centre of the complex. People travel in large numbers to Mayiladuthurai to bathe in this tank on the day of the new moon in the Tamil month of ''Aippasi'' (November\u2013December).{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} This bath purifies a person of sins because the waters of the river [[Ganges]] and other Indian rivers mingle with the waters of the [[Kaveri river]] in this tank on this particular day.<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp249\">[[#Ayyar|Ayyar]], p 249</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|title=South Indian shrines: illustrated|author=P. V. Jagadisa Ayyar|publisher=Madras Times Printing and Pub. Co.|year=1920|pages=|ref=Ayyar}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Mayiladuthurai Topics}}\n{{Famous Shiva temples}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n{{Mayiladuthurai district}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile:Mayuram mayuranathartemple2.jpg|Temple tank\nFile:Mayuram mayuranathartemple3.jpg|View from entrance\nFile:Mayuram mayuranathartemple4.jpg|Inner gopura\nFile:Mayuram mayuranathartemple5.jpg|Adhimayurathaswami vimana\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n[[Category:Padal Petra Stalam]]\n[[Category:Shiva temples in Mayiladuthurai district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Hindu temple\n| name               = Mayuranathaswamy temple\n| image              = Mayuranathar temple16.jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption            = ''Gopura'' of the Mayuranathaswamy Temple\n| map_type        = Tamil Nadu\n| map_caption        = \n| coordinates        = {{coord|11|0|N|79|15|E|type:landmark_region:LK|display=inline,title}}\n| native_name        =  \n| country            = [[India]]\n| state           = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| district           = [[Mayiladuthurai District|Mayiladuthurai ]]\n| location           = [[Mayiladuthurai]]\n| elevation_m        = \n| deity  = Mayuranathaswamy ([[Shiva]])\n| primary_deity_Goddess = \n| utsava_deity_Goddess= \n| facade_direction = \n| temple_tank        = \n| tower              = \n| festivals= \n| architecture       = [[Dravidian architecture|Dravidian]]\n| temple_quantity  = \n| monument_quantity= \n| inscriptions       = \n| year_completed         = \n| creator            = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Mayuranathaswamy Temple, Mayiladuthurai''' or Mayuranathar Temple is a Hindu temple in the town of [[Mayiladuthurai]] (formerly known as '''Mayavaram''' or '''Mayuram''') in the [[Mayiladuthurai District]] of [[Tamil Nadu]] in [[India]]. The temple is dedicated to Lord Mayuranathaswamy,\na form of [[Shiva]], and has given its name to the town itself.<ref name=\"imperialp238\">{{cite book|title=The Imperial Gazetteer of India 1908, Vol 17|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.181655|pages=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.181655/page/n228 238]|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1908}}</ref> The main icon is a  ''[[lingam]]'' and the presiding deity is called Mayuranathar because the Hindu goddess [[Parvathi]] worshipped Shiva here in the form of a ''[[peahen|mayura]]''.\n\nOn the day of the new moon in the Tamil month of ''Aippasi'' (November\u2013December), religious Hindus have a ceremonial bath in the temple tank as it is believed to purify them from sins. An annual dance festival called the Mayura Natyanjali festival is celebrated within the precincts of the temple each year.\n\n== Location ==\n\nThe Mayuranathaswami temple is located in the southern part of [[Mayiladuthurai]] about a mile from the [[Kaveri River]].<ref name=\"surap64\">{{cite book|title=Tourist Guide to Tamil Nadu|publisher=Sura Books|ISBN=978-81-7478-177-2|page=64}}</ref> The temple is  on the [[Chidambaram]]\u2013[[Thanjavur]] highway.<ref name=\"sacredtanksp227\">{{cite book|title=Sacred tanks of South India|publisher=C.P.R. Environmental Education Centre|author=Nanditha Krishna|year=2002|page=227}}</ref>\n\n== Significance ==\n[[Tiruvaiyaru|Thiruvayyaru]], [[Mayiladuthurai]], [[Thiruvidaimarudur|Thiruvidaimaruthur]], [[Thiruvenkadu]], Chayavanam and [[Srivanchiyam]] are considered equivalents of [[Kasi]]. Like in Kasi, where the city is centered around [[Kashi Vishwanath Temple]], the temples in these towns along the banks of river [[Cauvery]], namely [[Aiyarappar temple]] in Thiruvaiyaru, [[Mahalingeswarar Temple, Thiruvidaimarudur|Mahalingeswarar temple]] in [[Thiruvidaimarudur]], Mayuranathaswamy temple in [[Mayiladuthurai]], [[Sayavanam Chayavaneswarar Temple|Chayavaneswarar temple]] in Sayavanam, [[Swetharanyeswarar Temple|Swetharanyeswarar temple]] in [[Thiruvenkadu]], [[Vanchinadha Swamy Temple|Srivanchinadhaswamy Koil]] in [[Srivanchiyam]] are the centerpieces of the towns.<ref>{{cite book|title=Temples of Forgotten Glory: A Wide Angle Exposition|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=ItClDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT172&dq=aiyarappar+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixkLq1o4PpAhXaSH0KHdvOBIkQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=aiyarappar%20temple&f=false|page=172|first=Sekar|last=Venkatraman|isbn=9781645876250|publisher=Notion Press|year=2019}}</ref>\n\nIt is one of the shrines of the 275 [[Paadal Petra Sthalams]] - [[Shiva Temples of Tamil Nadu#Sthalams|Shiva Sthalams]] glorified in the early medieval ''[[Tevaram]]'' poems by Tamil Saivite [[Nayanars|Nayanar]] [[Tirugnanasambandar]].\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Mayuranathar temple18.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Hindu goddess [[Parvathi]] in the form of a [[peahen]] worshipping a ''[[shivalinga]]'']]\nThe presiding deity is a ''swayambhu lingam'' or a self-manifested ''[[lingam]]'', the symbol of the Hindu god [[Shiva]]. Shiva's consort is known by the names Abhayapradhambikai, Abhayambikai, Anjalanayaki and Anjalai.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} There are three smaller shrines to the Hindu god [[Ganesha]] and another to Shiva as [[Nataraja]] or \"Lord of Dance\".<ref name=Meena>{{cite book|title=Temples in South India|last=V.|first=Meena|publisher=Harikumar Arts|location=Kanniyakumari|year=1974|edition=1st|pages=36\u201337}}</ref> One of the sculptures in the temple represent Shiva embracing Goddess Parvathi.<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp271\">[[#Ayyar|Ayyar]], p 271</ref> According to [[Hindu mythology|mythology]], the goddess [[Parvathi]], the consort of [[Shiva]], once offended him.<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp271\" /> Shiva was so annoyed he cursed Parvathi to be born as a lowly [[peahen]].<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp271\" /> Later, when Parvathi repented, Shiva reduced this sentence.<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp271\" /> Parvathi had to pray first at [[Mylapore]] and then at [[Mayiladuthurai]], at the end of which she was ridden of her curse and became known as \"Abhayambal\".<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp271\" /> It is believed that [[Brahma]], [[Lakshmi]], sage [[Agastya]], [[Manmatha]], birds and animals worshipped Mayuranathar.<ref name=Meena/>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Mayuranathar8.jpg|200px|left|Image of the temple|thumb]]\nThe temple was built by the [[Medieval Cholas]].{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} The oldest inscriptions on the temple walls date to the time of [[Kulothunga Chola I]].<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp280\">[[#Ayyar|Ayyar]], p 280</ref> Massive renovations were carried out during  1907-1927 by Devakottai AL.VR.P.Veerappa Chettiar & Pethaperumal Chettiar<ref>https://alvrp.wordpress.com/al-vr-p-history/</ref> In May 1927, a temple entry of [[Dalits]] was organised on a big scale by the proponents of the [[Self Respect Movement]] thereby resulting in a huge clash.<ref name=\"rajathuaip224\">{{cite book|title=\tTowards a non-Brahmin millennium: from Iyothee Thass to Periyar|author=S. V. Rajathurai|publisher=Samya|year=1998|page=224|ISBN=978-81-85604-37-4}}</ref>\n\n== Architecture ==\n\nThe temple complex is {{convert|719|ft|m}} long and {{convert|520|ft|m}} wide.<ref>http://temple.dinamalar.com/en/new_en.php?id=214</ref> The ''gopura'' at the eastern entrance to the temple is nine storeys high<ref name=\"surap64\" /> and measures {{convert|194|ft|m}}.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} The idol of [[Durga]] near the northern entrance of the temple is expertly sculpted and differs from those in other temples.<ref name=\"surap64\" /> On the temple walls, there is the sculpture of a devotee trying to sever his head as an offering to the God.<ref name=\"surap64\" />\n\nThere is an expansive temple tank in the centre of the complex. People travel in large numbers to Mayiladuthurai to bathe in this tank on the day of the new moon in the Tamil month of ''Aippasi'' (November\u2013December).{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} This bath purifies a person of sins because the waters of the river [[Ganges]] and other Indian rivers mingle with the waters of the [[Kaveri river]] in this tank on this particular day.<ref name=\"southindianshrinesp249\">[[#Ayyar|Ayyar]], p 249</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{commons 